4. Data and Methodology
4.1 Dataset and Simulation Design
The dataset consists of 574 NBA regular-season game observations across the 2022-23 and 2023-24 seasons. Each observation includes closing moneyline odds, derived no-vig fair probabilities, point spread lines, simulated game outcomes, and simulated public betting ticket percentages.

An important transparency note: access to commercial odds archives was unavailable during this research period due to licensing constraints at sportsbookreviewsonline.com and The Action Network. The dataset was therefore constructed via simulation, with distributional parameters drawn from published academic literature. Moneyline odds distributions were calibrated to match NBA market ranges documented in Paul and Weinbach (2009). Home win rates were set to approximately 59%, consistent with long-run NBA regular-season data. Spread cover rates were calibrated near 50.8%. Public betting concentration patterns were modeled from Action Network aggregate studies on NBA markets. Due to access limitations, game outcomes and odds were simulated using distributional parameters consistent with published NBA betting market research, with results interpreted as illustrative of documented patterns rather than novel empirical findings.

The simulation applies a logistic outcome model of the form:

$$P(\text{home win}) = \frac{1}{1 + e^{-(\beta_0 + \beta_1 \cdot \Delta\text{NetRtg} + \beta_2 \cdot \text{RestDiff})}}$$

Where $\Delta\text{NetRtg}$ is the home team net rating advantage, $\text{RestDiff}$ is the home rest day advantage, and $\beta_0$ captures baseline home court. Coefficients were set consistent with ranges in NBA betting efficiency literature. Because the simulation was designed from parameters consistent with known FLB and public-bias findings, results reproduce expected patterns from the literature rather than independently discovering new ones. This paper is best understood as a methodology framework and calibration study.
4.2 Implied Probability and Fair Odds
For each observation, no-vig fair probabilities are computed using the normalization method in Section 3.1. Games are bucketed into six implied-probability ranges to examine the FLB across the full market spectrum. Closing lines are used throughout, consistent with the convention that closing prices represent the most information-rich market signal.
4.3 Statistical Tests
For H1 (favorite-longshot bias), I apply a one-sample z-test comparing simulated win rates for chalk games (fair probability above 70%) against their market-implied probabilities. The null hypothesis is that simulated win rates equal implied probabilities across all buckets.

For H2 (public betting bias), I compare spread cover rates between high-public simulated games (home receiving above 70% of tickets) and low-public games (below 45%) using a two-sample t-test. The null hypothesis is no difference in cover rates between groups.


