The pattern at the extremes is the most informative. In the big underdog bucket (implied below 45%), simulated win rates exceed implied probabilities by +12.0 percentage points, reproducing the longshot overpricing documented in the FLB literature. In the chalk bucket (above 78%), simulated teams win 66.7% against a market-implied rate of 78.7%, a –12.0 percentage-point gap. The small chalk sample (n=12) means that specific figure carries a wide confidence interval and should be read carefully.

The z-test on chalk games (fair probability above 70%, n = 81) yields a deviation of –6.9 percentage points, z = –1.42, p = 0.156. This does not meet the p < 0.05 threshold. Failure to reject the null does not imply absence of effect; the directional consistency across all six buckets is meaningful, but the estimated effect size, while economically significant, is statistically inconclusive at this sample size. Studies achieving significance in FLB research typically use 3,000–10,000+ game samples spanning multiple sports.

