6. Discussion
6.1 What the Simulated Results Reproduce
The simulation reproduces patterns broadly consistent with the NBA and multi-sport betting efficiency literature. Near-zero deviation in the mid-range probability buckets (45–60%) matches what efficient, heavily-arbitraged markets should show. Distortions concentrate at the extremes where public behavioral tendencies are strongest and books have the most pricing flexibility.

This is consistent with Levitt's (2004) model of books as active position-takers. In that framework, books shade prices toward public demand and accept lopsided exposure when they judge recreational bettors to be systematically wrong. The win rate versus cover rate divergence in high-public simulated games is the clearest illustration of this mechanism in the data. Because the simulation was calibrated to parameters consistent with these findings, the reproduction validates the model's behavior rather than independently confirming the effects. That distinction is important to keep in mind.
6.2 The Product Mix Problem
One finding requiring no simulation to establish is the hold rate gradient in Table 1. The math is deterministic: a four-leg parlay at -110 per leg carries approximately 22.1% hold versus 4.55% for a straight spread bet. A bettor placing four-leg parlays faces roughly five times the structural cost per dollar wagered compared to someone placing straight bets. DraftKings' increasing product mix toward parlay and SGP products raises expected bettor losses per dollar wagered significantly, and this shift is documented in the company's own investor materials as a revenue driver.

Sports betting products are not subject to the standardized expected-loss disclosures required of most other financial products. The complexity of multi-leg products makes pricing harder to evaluate for most consumers. That is worth noting as a consumer finance observation, independent of anything the simulation shows.
6.3 Limitations
Three limitations should be kept in mind.

First, the dataset is simulated. The study is a methodology framework and calibration exercise. The results confirm the model behaves consistently with published literature, which is useful but not the same as discovering patterns in real archival data. Future work should replicate this analysis on live closing-line archives to confirm directional findings at scale.

Second, 574 games is a small sample for detecting effects that are inherently noisy. Published FLB studies achieving significance use 3,000–10,000+ game samples. Extending this to real multi-season data is the direct path to stronger statistical claims.

Third, public ticket percentages here are ticket-count weighted. Dollar-weighted figures would better isolate recreational from professional money, since sharp bettors move lines with dollars rather than ticket volume. That data is harder to access freely but would sharpen the public bias analysis considerably.


7. Conclusion
The mechanics of how DraftKings makes money are not mysterious once the math is written out. Every bet carries a structural cost to the bettor. That cost is derivable from the offered odds. And it varies dramatically by product type in ways that are not communicated to most participants. A recreational bettor who places a four-leg parlay instead of a straight spread has roughly quadrupled the structural edge against them per dollar wagered, and the probability that they know this going in is low.

The simulation study reproduces what the literature predicts: a monotonic favorite-longshot pattern across probability buckets and a cover rate gap between low- and high-public games that is consistent with line-shading behavior. Neither finding reaches conventional statistical significance at 574 observations, which is reported honestly. Failure to reject the null does not imply absence of effect. It means the methodology needs a larger real-data sample to generate strong statistical claims, and that is the paper's clearest limitation and most direct path forward.

The broader observation is that sports betting is a surprisingly clean case study for consumer financial market behavior. The tendencies that cause bettors to overpay for popular teams,  overweight recent outcomes, follow media narratives, and seek the excitement of longshot payoffs show up in retail investing, insurance, and essentially any market with an information gap between seller and buyer. Sports betting just makes the pricing math visible and the resolution date concrete. The problem is not that the pricing is hidden. Most people simply never look at it.

